explanation:
OS_CHECK_POINTER - macro used at the top of OS_DirectoryRead; its expansion may call logging or helper routines that could use memcmp on strings.
OS_ObjectIdGetById - first call in the function; its implementation may perform string comparisons (e.g. name lookups) and thus could contain prohibited memcmp usage.
OS_ObjectIdRelease - called unconditionally after the impl call; its implementation may also perform object-name handling or cleanup that could use memcmp.
OS_DirRead_Impl - the underlying directory-read implementation invoked by OS_DirectoryRead; this is the most likely place to compare directory entry names (null-terminated strings) and therefore must be checked for memcmp.
OS_ObjectIndexFromToken - called by OS_DirRead_Impl (per the call graph); may perform token-to-name/index mapping or comparisons involving strings.
OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit - called by OS_ObjectIdGetById; transaction initialization code may perform checks that compare strings.
OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex - called by OS_ObjectIdGetById; may perform conversions/lookup using string comparisons.
OS_ObjectIdConvertToken - called by OS_ObjectIdGetById; may manipulate/compare identifiers or names (potential memcmp usage).
OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel - called by OS_ObjectIdGetById; cancellation/cleanup routines may include string handling.
OS_ObjectIdTransactionFinish - called by OS_ObjectIdRelease; finish/cleanup routines may include string handling.
OS_printf - logging/printf wrapper used elsewhere (and possibly by macros like OS_CHECK_POINTER); implementations or wrappers may perform string operations that could use memcmp.

Rationale: to determine whether OS_DirectoryRead (or anything it calls) violates the MISRA rule banning memcmp for null-terminated string comparison, the analysis must inspect the body of every directly called function and the immediate helper functions they invoke that could plausibly compare strings. The list above contains the direct callees and their closely related subcalls (and the pointer-check macro and logging function) that are the plausible locations for such forbidden memcmp use.
